"""
RTS-96 (24-bus) reliability with:
  - 6-state cyber-physical availability model for generators and lines
  - Truncated contingency enumeration (up to order K)
  - DC-OPF (linear screening model; placeholder for future AC-OPF)
  - FULL component-wise Sobol sensitivity:
      * every generator gets its own 8 transition-rate multipliers
      * every line gets its own 8 transition-rate multipliers
      * plus wind_k, wind_mean, load_sigma
  - Full result saving for later analysis

Dimension
---------
32 generators * 8 rates = 256
38 lines      * 8 rates = 304
Wind/load                =   3
Total Sobol dimension    = 563

Important
---------
This is extremely expensive. With first-order + total-order Sobol only:
    total evaluations ~= N * (D + 2) = N * 565
So even N=2 => 1130 full model evaluations.

Saved outputs
-------------
1) sobol_results_full_component.csv
   - all Sobol sampled inputs (all 563 variables)
   - derived wind_scale
   - outputs: LOLP, EENS, enum_mass, tail_mass, n_contingencies
   - mean generator / line availability

2) component_availability_full_component.csv
   - per-sample availability for every generator and line
   - columns: p_up_G1 ... p_up_G32, p_up_L1 ... p_up_L38

3) sobol_indices_summary_full_component.csv
   - S1 / ST / confidence intervals for LOLP and EENS for every input variable

4) nominal_component_rates_full_component.csv
   - nominal transition rates for every generator and every line

This model is internally consistent:
- component outage uncertainty is handled only in the OUTER contingency layer
- inner Monte Carlo samples only wind and load uncertainty
"""

